  <p class="faq-subtitle">Everything you need to know about lawn mower repair services.</p>
  <div class="faq-accordion">
    <div class="faq-item open">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>How long does a typical lawn mower repair take in Denver?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>Most basic repairs like blade sharpening or tune-ups can be completed in 1-3 business days. More complex repairs involving engine work or parts ordering typically take 1-2 weeks. Some shops offer same-day service for simple repairs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>What are the signs that my lawn mower engine is blown?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>Common signs of a blown engine include excessive smoke, loud knocking or grinding noises, loss of power, oil leaks, and the engine not starting at all. If you notice these symptoms, it's best to have a professional diagnose the issue immediately.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>Is repairing a lawn mower actually a good idea?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>Yes, repairing a lawn mower is often a good investment, especially if the repair cost is less than half the price of a new mower. Regular maintenance and timely repairs can extend your mower's lifespan significantly and save you money in the long run.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>What does a complete lawn mower tune-up include?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>A complete tune-up typically includes changing the oil and air filter, replacing or cleaning the spark plug, sharpening the blades, cleaning the deck, checking and adjusting belts, inspecting the fuel system, and testing the engine performance.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>What steps are involved in fixing a lawn mower?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>The repair process typically involves diagnosing the problem, disassembling necessary components, cleaning or replacing faulty parts, reassembling the mower, and testing to ensure everything works properly. The specific steps depend on the type of repair needed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>How can I tell if the spark plug in my mower has gone bad?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>Signs of a bad spark plug include difficulty starting the engine, rough idling, reduced power, increased fuel consumption, and visible damage like carbon buildup or a cracked ceramic insulator. A professional can test the spark plug to confirm if it needs replacement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item faq-item-blurred-light">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>How frequently should I get my lawn mower serviced?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>It's recommended to service your lawn mower at least once per year, ideally before the mowing season begins. For heavy use or commercial mowers, consider servicing every 25-50 hours of operation. Regular maintenance helps prevent costly repairs and extends your mower's life.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item faq-item-blurred">
      <div class="faq-question">
        <span>What happens if I skip oil changes on my lawn mower?</span>
        <span class="faq-arrow">▼</span>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        <p>Skipping oil changes can lead to engine overheating, increased friction, premature engine wear, and eventually engine failure. Dirty oil loses its lubricating properties and can cause serious damage. Regular oil changes are essential for maintaining your mower's performance and longevity.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <button class="btn-show-more" id="showMoreBtn">Show More</button>
  </section>
</div>

<script>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    const showMoreBtn = document.getElementById('showMoreBtn');
    const blurredItems = document.querySelectorAll('.faq-item-blurred, .faq-item-blurred-light');
    let isExpanded = false;

    if (showMoreBtn && blurredItems.length > 0) {
      showMoreBtn.addEventListener('click', function() {
        isExpanded = !isExpanded;
        
        blurredItems.forEach(function(item) {
          if (isExpanded) {
            item.classList.add('show');
          } else {
            item.classList.remove('show');
          }
        });

        showMoreBtn.textContent = isExpanded ? 'Show Less' : 'Show More';
      });
    }
  });
</script>

